en government: its characteristics, preconditions, benefits, and its relation to modern diplomacy. The mindset of a democracy-rooted diplomat with a working experience in an increasingly autocratic regime lends a particular perspective to the topics discussed. These topics include the fight against corruption, the protection of civil society, crisis prevention, education, economy, international relations, applied humanities, and the use of the social and traditional media to achieve policy goals. This book presents modern, “people-friendly” diplomacy in an era in which public officials are increasingly expected to be transparent and engaged.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracy. 0aDiplomacy. 0aDiplomatszUnited StatesvInterviews. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / Diplomacy.2bisacsh  adiplomacy.  aevolving autocracy.  agovernance.  ailliberal democracy.  aopen society.1 aGoodfriend, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHargittai, Istvan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2023z978311079759608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633866092?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633866092423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633866092/original  a978-3-11-079759-6  Central European Univer